			<h2>About the Project</h2>
			<p>
				On the surface, Sweet Little Hauntings is an online art shop that sells a variety of trinkets and stationary items, such as enamel pins, acrylic charms, and stickers with a pastel goth aesthetic. However, with a bit of digging the website becomes a stage for a secret narrative of loss and grief that site users can unlock by solving hidden puzzles. Both the shop and the narrative take inspiration from finding comfort in discomfort, the darker aspects of life, and what lies beyond.
			</p>
			<p>
				This unfiction project explores experimental methods of storytelling by inviting the site visitors to dive down a rabbit hole of mystery and horror. It takes inspiration from previous works like House of Leaves by Mark Z. Danielewski, Omega Mart from Meow Wolf, and videos like Unedited Footage of a Bear, all of which start out relatively normal but quickly spiral into something strange, fantastic, and horrifying. Sweet Little Hauntings aims to make its audience think and feel in ways they may not experience in their everyday lives.
			</p>
		</div>

		<div class="asides">
			<div class="aside-box">
				<h3>What is Unfiction?</h3>
				<p>
					Unfiction is a method of storytelling where a narrative is presented as if it were real, allowing the audience to fully suspend their disbelief and immerse themselves in the story. They typically start out grounded in our reality, and then integrate more fantastical, supernatural, or horrific elements while still maintaining the insistence on reality.
				</p>
			</div>

			<div class="aside-box">
				<h3>What is an ARG?</h3>
				<p>
					An ARG, or Alternate Reality Game, is a type of unfiction that requires audience participation, typically in the form of solving puzzles that are hidden within the presentation of the story. Tradionally, an ARG will have a community working together to solve the clues the creator has planted, and the creator will release new parts of the story when the last part has been solved.
				</p>
			</div>			
		</div>

		</div>
		

